(40, 9, 30, 19, 146, 8, 8, 'their eyes were opened', 'Opening of the Eyes', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine healing, as both passages mention the act of opening the eyes. In Matthew, Jesus opens the eyes of the blind, while Psalms speaks of the Lord opening the eyes of the blind, emphasizing God''s power to restore sight.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 30, 23, 35, 5, 5, NULL, 'Healing of the Blind', 'This connection highlights the theme of healing, as both passages refer to the opening of eyes. Matthew 9:30 emphasizes the miraculous act of Jesus opening the eyes of the blind, paralleling Isaiah 35:5, which prophesies that the eyes of the blind shall be opened.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 31, 41, 7, 36, 36, 'spread abroad his fame', 'Spread of Fame', 'Both passages emphasize the act of spreading news about Jesus. In Matthew, the fame is spread abroad, while in Mark, despite Jesus'' charge to tell no one, they published it even more.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 31, 40, 9, 26, 26, NULL, 'Connection of Fame Spread', 'Both passages emphasize the spreading of fame, indicating a significant event that captured public attention. The repetition of the phrase ''went abroad into all that land'' and ''spread abroad his fame'' highlights the impact of the events described.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 31, 41, 1, 44, 45, 'spread abroad his fame', 'Spread of Jesus'' Fame', 'Both passages emphasize the spreading of Jesus'' fame after healing. In Matthew, the healed individuals spread his fame, while in Mark, the healed man publishes the matter, leading to Jesus being unable to enter the city openly.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 32, 40, 4, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Healing and Possession', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of those possessed with devils. Matthew 9:32 specifically mentions a dumb man possessed with a devil, while Matthew 4:24 lists those possessed with devils among various ailments brought to Jesus for healing.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 32, 40, 12, 22, 24, 'dumb man possessed with a devil', 'Healing of the Possessed', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of individuals possessed by demons, specifically mentioning a dumb man. The connection highlights the miraculous power of Jesus in casting out devils and restoring speech and sight.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 32, 42, 11, 14, 14, 'dumb man possessed with a devil', 'Healing of the Dumb Man', 'Both passages emphasize the healing of a dumb man possessed by a devil. In Matthew, the focus is on the man''s condition before healing, while Luke describes the healing event and the subsequent speaking. This connection highlights the miraculous power of Jesus over demonic possession.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 32, 41, 9, 17, 27, 'dumb man possessed with a devil', 'Connection of Dumb Spirits', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of a ''dumb'' spirit affecting individuals. The SOURCE verse mentions a ''dumb man possessed with a devil,'' while the TARGET passage describes a ''dumb spirit'' afflicting a boy. This connection highlights the theme of Jesus'' authority over such spirits.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 33, 2, 4, 11, 12, 'the dumb spake', 'Connection of Speech and Healing', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of speech and healing. In Matthew, the casting out of the devil leads to the dumb speaking, while in Exodus, God asserts His power over those who are dumb, promising to guide Moses in speech.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 33, 23, 35, 6, 6, NULL, 'Healing and Restoration Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing of the mute, with Matthew 9:33 showcasing a specific instance of this healing, while Isaiah 35:6 anticipates the joyful singing of the dumb as part of future restoration. This connection highlights the fulfillment of prophetic expectations in the ministry of Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 33, 41, 7, 32, 37, 'the dumb spake', 'Healing of Speech and Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize miraculous healings involving speech and hearing. In Matthew, the dumb speak after a devil is cast out, while in Mark, a deaf man is healed and begins to speak plainly.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 33, 12, 5, 8, 8, NULL, 'Miracles and Prophetic Authority', 'Both passages emphasize the recognition of divine authority through miraculous acts. In Matthew, the crowd marvels at the healing, while in 2 Kings, Elisha demonstrates his prophetic power, leading to acknowledgment of a prophet in Israel.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 33, 19, 76, 1, 1, NULL, 'God''s Presence in Israel', 'This connection highlights the recognition of God''s power in Israel. Both passages emphasize the marvel of God''s actions among the people, showcasing His greatness and presence.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 33, 24, 32, 20, 20, 'It was never so seen in Israel', 'Signs and Wonders in Israel', 'This connection highlights the theme of miraculous signs and wonders performed in Israel. Both passages emphasize the extraordinary acts of God that provoke amazement among the people.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 33, 40, 15, 30, 31, NULL, 'Healing and Marveling Multitudes', 'Both passages emphasize the miraculous healing of the dumb, leading to amazement among the multitudes. The phrase ''the dumb to speak'' appears in both, highlighting the significance of this miracle in drawing attention to Jesus'' authority.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 34, 42, 11, 15, 15, 'casteth out devils through', 'Accusation of Demonic Power', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation that Jesus casts out demons through a demonic source. The specific mention of ''Beelzebub'' in Luke parallels the reference to ''the prince of the devils'' in Matthew, highlighting a common theme of opposition to Jesus'' authority.', 'theme', 0.398, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 34, 41, 3, 22, 22, 'prince of the devils', 'Accusations of Demonic Power', 'Both passages emphasize the accusation against Jesus that he casts out demons by the power of evil. The specific mention of ''prince of the devils'' in both verses highlights a direct parallel in the claims made by the religious leaders.', 'parallel', 0.384, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 9, 34, 40, 12, 23, 24, 'through the prince of the devils', 'Pharisees'' Accusation of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the Pharisees'' claim that Jesus casts out devils through Beelzebub, the prince of the devils. This connection highlights the ongoing opposition Jesus faced from the Pharisees regarding his miraculous works.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
